amous Two Treatises of Government. In his works on epistemology and education, Locke describes morality as a construct and human nature as malleable. Drawing on Foucault's concept of discipline, Baltes reconsiders Locke's liberalism and shows that it requires citizens governed not by natural law but habit, that is, subjects who are constructed by carefully controlled space and visibility and regulated in their conduct to become capable of self-government. The Empire of Habit thus offers not only a new reading of one of the most important political philosophers of the Western tradition but also newinsight into our own political liberalism. John Baltes is an independent scholar of political theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aKnowledge, Theory ofxEarly works to 1800. 0aLiberalismxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitics & Economics. 4aSocial History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aJohn Locke.  aauthoritarianism.  acapitalism.  acommunism.  aconservatism.  ademocracy.  adictatorship.  ainternational relations.  aliberalism.  aphilosophy.  apolitical science.  apsychology.  asocialism.  asociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782047049?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782047049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782047049/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles